495":"1495","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","about 1494":"omkring 1494","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Skotland"},"nl":{"1478–1500":"1478–1500","1474–1521":"1474–1521","1495–1550":"1495–1550","1510–Female":"1510–Overleden","1448–Male":"1448–Overleden","1450–Female":"1450–Overleden","1448":"1448","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1510":"1510","1521":"1521","1474":"1474","1495":"1495","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","about 1494":"circa 1494","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland"},"en":{"1478–1500":"1478–1500","1474–1521":"1474–1521","1495–1550":"1495–1550","1510–Female":"1510–Deceased","1448–Male":"1448–Deceased","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","1448":"1448","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1510":"1510","1521":"1521","1474":"1474","1495":"1495","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","about 1494":"about 1494","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"McInnes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   McInnis  .","History: This is the name of a Highland Scottish clan claiming descent from Angus, brother of Fergus Mòr Mac Earca, legendary king of Dal Riata in the 6th century. Their traditional family seat was at Kinlochaline Castle in Morvern."],"variants":[{"name":"McInnis","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aonghuis</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Aonghus</i> (see   Angus  ). See also   McInnes  , compare Irish   McGinnis  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Peggy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Margaret  , frequently used as an independent given name in the 1920s and 30s;  see  Peg ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Peggy McInnes was born in 1478, in Edinburgh, Scotland, her father, John Mc Innes, was 30 and her mother, Sarah McColl, was 28. She married Ewen Morrison about 1494, in Edinburgh, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1500, in her hometown, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1478–1500":"1478–1500","1474–1521":"1474–1521","1495–1550":"1495–1550","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","1448":"1448","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1510":"1510","1521":"1521","1474":"1474","1495":"1495","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","about 1494":"umbes 1494","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland"},"fi":{"1478–1500":"1478–1500","1474–1521":"1474–1521","1495–1550":"1495–1550","1510–Female":"1510–Kuollut","1448–Male":"1448–Kuollut","1450–Female":"1450–Kuollut","1448":"